{
  "texts": [
    "That is, if learning nothing new resulted in zero signal propagation, the residual connection shifted the input representation slightly without significantly modifying the token representation so that learning can continue without degradation.",
    "When training deep networks, in addition to the vanishing gradient problem, the gradients calculated to adjust parameters can also explode if they get too large.",
    "For example, multiplying the number 10 only five times yields 10 5 = 100,000.",
    "Large gradients make the training unstable because of parameter oscillations that prevent training convergence.",
    "Normalization helps to prevent both vanishing and exploding gradients while increasing training speed and reducing bias (Ba et al. 2016)."
  ]
}